Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one shared HttpClient/state across the app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — fresh state each time a page is navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a clean page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared state (auth tokens, caches). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a fresh VM — no stale data from a previous visit. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModel lifetime. A new page binds to a new VM, avoiding UI state bleed between navigations. |

**Key takeaway:** Services that manage connections or shared state → **Singleton**. UI-layer objects (pages, VMs) that should reset per navigation → **Transient**. Avoid `Scoped` in MAUI — there's no built-in scope-per-page like in ASP.NET.
